  "response": "The human eye can distinguish approximately 10 million different colors and hues. This impressive range is due to the complex structure of the human eye, specifically the cone cells in the retina. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. Cone cells:\n- There are three types of cone cells\n- Each type is sensitive to different wavelengths of light (red, green, and blue)\n- These cones can combine to create a wide spectrum of colors\n\n2. Color perception factors:\n- Different wavelengths of light\n- Variations in brightness and saturation\n- Individual variations in color perception\n\n3. Estimated color range:\n- Around 10 million distinguishable colors\n- Some researchers suggest the range could be between 7-10 million colors\n\n4. Limitations:\n- Color perception can vary between individuals\n- Age, eye health, and genetic factors can affect color perception\n- Some people have color blindness, which reduces their color range\n\nWhile 10 million colors sounds precise, the exact number is still a subject of scientific research and debate. The human visual system is incredibly complex and continues to be studied by researchers.",
